Let the $y$-intercept be $c$;
since this is the $y$-intercept, plugging in $x=0$ immediately gives $c$.</think> 
<answer>Because of the symmetry of parabolas, the vertex is halfway between the two points with the same $y$-value, so it is at $(x,3)$ where $x=\frac{-3+1}{2}=-1$.  Plugging this in gives $3=a(-1)^2+b(-1) +c=a-b+c$.  Also, because it is a $y$-intercept, we have $c=0$ by the same logic as above.  All together, we have $3=a-b$ and $0=c$.  Since $b=3-a$, we have $100a+10b+c=100a+10(3-a)+0=\boxed{90+90a}$.</answer>

